                "title": "Organizing a DjangoGirls in Africa- Excerpt from #DjangoGirlsLagos with lessons learned from #DjangoGirlsWindhoek",
                "url": "http://blog.djangogirls.org/post/144289849283",
                "description": "<p>This blog post was written by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/aishaxbello\">Aisha Bello</a><a href=\"http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.flickr.com%2Fphotos%2Fdjangogirls%2F26539157245%2Fin%2Falbum-72157667360931465%2F&amp;t=NzAwMzM2NjBiZDllYWVkOWJiYzE1OTkxY2Q3ZWFkNjU1ZmQyYzEyZSxXMzhVc1U3NA%3D%3D\"></a>. Thanks ❤️<br/></p><hr><p>So earlier this year in January. I joined a team of amazing ladies to organize DjangoGirls in Namibia. Helen did a great job in analysing what it entails <a href=\"http://blog.djangogirls.org/post/139654610313/django-girls-workshop-in-windhoek-namibia\">in a blog post here</a> but I am writing with a different <a href=\"http://blog.djangogirls.org/post/139654610313/django-girls-workshop-in-windhoek-namibia\">purpose</a> to bring to limelight the challenges and how I quickly had to learn how to quickly overcome them during the Lagos workshop. Even though Africa is a really huge continent and I could say I experienced organizing in Namibia another African country which had many similarities, Nothing quite prepared me for DjangoGirls the Nigerian way #Lagos Edition.</p>\n<p>For DjangoGirls Lagos we had a total of 137 applications with only space of 30 attendees. There were so many great and quality applications and haven gotten help of 3 other DjangoGirls organizers it didn’t make the process easy as they <a href=\"https://twitter.com/laceynwilliams/status/693142550861864960\">had ...</a></p>",
